1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:00,650 --> 00:00:01,150
Three, four.

3
00:00:32,450 --> 00:00:33,570
So tomorrow is the singing gig.

4
00:00:33,570 --> 00:00:33,910
Yes?

5
00:01:09,260 --> 00:01:09,780
Tomas!

6
00:01:15,250 --> 00:01:16,250
This is modern, you see?

7
00:01:17,550 --> 00:01:18,650
For God's sake, what happened?

8
00:01:18,850 --> 00:01:20,970
My new image for my young audience.

9
00:01:21,170 --> 00:01:22,950
What young audience of yours?

10
00:01:23,470 --> 00:01:23,990
See?

11
00:01:24,110 --> 00:01:27,150
You're trying to suggest again that only old ladies come to my shows.

12
00:01:27,230 --> 00:01:28,850
But Kostelec opened my eyes.

13
00:01:28,930 --> 00:01:29,870
That was an exception.

14
00:01:30,450 --> 00:01:31,330
Unfortunately.

15
00:01:31,330 --> 00:01:33,010
But you know what energy it gave me?

16
00:01:33,240 --> 00:01:35,380
Seeing a young person at my concert, and so many?

17
00:01:35,740 --> 00:01:37,700
There was only one old lady, just one.

18
00:01:37,740 --> 00:01:39,160
Everyone else was under twenty.

19
00:01:41,550 --> 00:01:44,550
That was the history teacher from 8B. She brought them to see what real socialism looked like.

20
00:01:44,850 --> 00:01:49,250
And did they like it?

21
00:01:50,950 --> 00:01:53,350
On the way from the concert they threw her into a creek.

22
00:01:54,250 --> 00:01:56,750
Tomas, your career is in crisis.

23
00:01:58,650 --> 00:02:01,150
Dolni Loucky, five paying.

24
00:02:01,350 --> 00:02:02,420
Chroustov, seven.

25
00:02:02,850 --> 00:02:04,650
Two paid with firewood.

26
00:02:05,150 --> 00:02:07,300
Destne in the Orlicke Mountains, nineteen.

27
00:02:07,300 --> 00:02:07,520
Well.

28
00:02:08,650 --> 00:02:10,950
They came to shelter from the storm.

29
00:02:12,150 --> 00:02:13,830
Tomas, we need to do something.

30
00:02:14,150 --> 00:02:15,810
And this isn't enough?

31
00:02:15,810 --> 00:02:18,090
Stefan says a costume change is passe.

32
00:02:18,110 --> 00:02:19,790
These days only a sex change works.

33
00:02:20,950 --> 00:02:22,350
But we can't wait.

34
00:02:23,050 --> 00:02:24,350
So where's Stefan?

35
00:02:24,380 --> 00:02:24,940
Pabecky?

36
00:02:24,940 --> 00:02:26,980
Yes, I went to consult with him.

37
00:02:26,980 --> 00:02:28,460
But everyone hates him.

38
00:02:28,700 --> 00:02:29,600
Who's everyone?

39
00:02:29,660 --> 00:02:30,280
In the business.

40
00:02:30,480 --> 00:02:35,060
Well, his methods may be a bit unconventional, but he boosts anyone's popularity.

41
00:02:35,180 --> 00:02:37,180
Gott says he'll punch him.

42
00:02:37,650 --> 00:02:40,450
Because thanks to him he's stuck with a young wife and two kids.

43
00:02:40,950 --> 00:02:43,230
But look how well he sells.

44
00:02:43,750 --> 00:02:45,650
I don't want any more kids.

45
00:02:46,150 --> 00:02:47,930
Look at Stefan's successes.

46
00:02:47,930 --> 00:02:49,310
Well, Richard Miller.

47
00:02:49,310 --> 00:02:55,050
Career in decline, but he just had to strip in Zlin and he was sold out for half a year.

48
00:02:55,190 --> 00:02:56,570
But there were drugs involved, right?

49
00:02:56,690 --> 00:02:57,170
Drugs?

50
00:02:58,650 --> 00:03:01,550
Stefan always says, scandal is the best advertising.

51
00:03:02,650 --> 00:03:03,650
Horrible.

52
00:03:04,350 --> 00:03:07,650
Rychtar said the same thing when Stefan told him to marry Bartosova.

53
00:03:08,750 --> 00:03:13,170
Good Lord, have we sunk so low that only those with no shame whatsoever are popular?

54
00:03:13,550 --> 00:03:14,950
And they brag about it?

55
00:03:15,550 --> 00:03:17,150
Tomas, I'll say just two words.

56
00:03:18,350 --> 00:03:19,250
Leos Mares.

57
00:03:24,650 --> 00:03:26,050
This is always how it starts.

58
00:03:27,150 --> 00:03:30,930
For now you're just four individuals who each think they're here on their own.

59
00:03:30,930 --> 00:03:34,650
Today you still feel like you're Jura, Jira, Zdenda, Simca.

60
00:03:34,730 --> 00:03:35,130
Simona.

61
00:03:35,210 --> 00:03:35,450
Simca.

62
00:03:35,510 --> 00:03:39,130
Every extra syllable is wasted time, and time is the decisive factor in the game for the customer.

63
00:03:41,050 --> 00:03:44,950
You probably think your job will be frying fries and mopping the floor, right?

64
00:03:46,650 --> 00:03:47,250
Wrong.

65
00:03:49,650 --> 00:03:50,510
Great.

66
00:03:50,850 --> 00:03:54,550
Who can figure out why I'm going to say this word?

67
00:03:56,050 --> 00:03:56,750
Volleyball.

68
00:03:59,990 --> 00:04:00,550
Well.

69
00:04:02,350 --> 00:04:03,290
Because it has "volley" in it?

70
00:04:03,290 --> 00:04:03,850
No.

71
00:04:05,350 --> 00:04:06,350
Keep thinking.

72
00:04:06,670 --> 00:04:07,910
Are there any options?

73
00:04:07,910 --> 00:04:11,450
Alright, hint: what's the most important thing in volleyball?

74
00:04:12,460 --> 00:04:13,020
The dig?

75
00:04:13,380 --> 00:04:14,460
For me, the serve.

76
00:04:14,460 --> 00:04:16,250
Yes, but what's even more important?

77
00:04:20,410 --> 00:04:20,970
The team.

78
00:04:23,080 --> 00:04:23,860
Yeah, I knew that too.

79
00:04:23,860 --> 00:04:25,380
Volleyball is a team sport, after all.

80
00:04:25,380 --> 00:04:25,820
Right.

81
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:27,240
And fast food is too.

82
00:04:27,240 --> 00:04:30,050
I'm the captain of the Castle, I spike, the guy in the kitchen serves.

83
00:04:31,350 --> 00:04:34,520
And all of you are a team that only wins when it cooperates perfectly.

84
00:04:34,520 --> 00:04:34,860
Got it?

85
00:04:35,260 --> 00:04:35,700
Good.

86
00:04:36,450 --> 00:04:37,850
Pop quiz.

87
00:04:39,540 --> 00:04:40,620
Who is the customer?

88
00:04:40,740 --> 00:04:41,960
The opponent, God no.

89
00:04:44,650 --> 00:04:47,650
The customer is the ball that must not hit the ground.

90
00:04:48,140 --> 00:04:48,580
Got it?

91
00:04:50,750 --> 00:04:52,150
So, what did you take away from this?

92
00:04:56,750 --> 00:04:58,230
That we'll be playing volleyball?

93
00:04:58,230 --> 00:04:58,670
No.

94
00:05:10,450 --> 00:05:10,890
Iva!

95
00:05:11,450 --> 00:05:12,450
Want some Mega Breast?

96
00:05:12,560 --> 00:05:13,080
Out.

97
00:05:16,150 --> 00:05:18,180
Iva, Mom's bringing us dinner from the new job today.

98
00:05:18,180 --> 00:05:19,000
She can get some for you too.

99
00:05:21,250 --> 00:05:22,710
Spicy Mega Breast.

100
00:05:22,710 --> 00:05:23,830
Cool burger menu.

101
00:05:24,050 --> 00:05:24,870
Happy Cheese.

102
00:05:26,350 --> 00:05:27,850
Thanks, but I don't eat that junk.

103
00:05:28,070 --> 00:05:28,950
What junk?

104
00:05:29,950 --> 00:05:34,430
A proper slab of happy meat with a generous portion of happy cheese in a super bun, it'll make you drool.

105
00:05:34,750 --> 00:05:36,250
What does it say, Happy Cheese?

106
00:05:37,980 --> 00:05:40,380
Fried patty made from animal-based substance.

107
00:05:40,760 --> 00:05:45,080
Soy extract with cheese flavor, bun made of flour, fat, preservatives and sugar.

108
00:05:45,320 --> 00:05:46,620
Contains monosodium glutamate.

109
00:05:47,850 --> 00:05:50,950
Simona says decent people don't read the fine print.

110
00:05:56,940 --> 00:05:57,600
Hello.

111
00:05:57,740 --> 00:05:59,160
Hello, what can I offer you?

112
00:05:59,420 --> 00:06:00,700
Just a salad, please.

113
00:06:00,960 --> 00:06:03,200
Regular or a fit salad with reduced sugar content?

114
00:06:03,660 --> 00:06:04,460
The fit one.

115
00:06:04,680 --> 00:06:04,960
Fit!

116
00:06:05,320 --> 00:06:05,800
Fit!

117
00:06:06,120 --> 00:06:06,820
Fit, got it!

118
00:06:06,960 --> 00:06:07,380
Great.

119
00:06:07,480 --> 00:06:08,220
With mayonnaise?

120
00:06:08,680 --> 00:06:09,780
God, no mayonnaise.

121
00:06:09,920 --> 00:06:10,840
No worries.

122
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:12,680
Happy mayo is a new type of mayonnaise.

123
00:06:12,760 --> 00:06:14,120
No trace of oil or eggs.

124
00:06:14,820 --> 00:06:15,300
Really?

125
00:06:15,650 --> 00:06:20,250
Plus, with a salad with happy mayo we offer our choco bomb or fries at a special price.

126
00:06:20,650 --> 00:06:22,350
Definitely not the choco bomb.

127
00:06:22,350 --> 00:06:23,700
So fries then.

128
00:06:23,700 --> 00:06:24,280
Fries!

129
00:06:24,420 --> 00:06:25,000
Fries!

130
00:06:26,950 --> 00:06:27,650
Yeah, fries.

131
00:06:29,720 --> 00:06:30,300
Ketchup?

132
00:06:31,970 --> 00:06:32,550
Two.

133
00:06:32,550 --> 00:06:35,710
Alright, so that's two ketchups, fries, happy mayo.

134
00:06:35,710 --> 00:06:38,730
How about we bundle it all into our super deal menu?

135
00:06:38,850 --> 00:06:40,110
So you don't overpay.

136
00:06:42,050 --> 00:06:45,050
Three ketchups for the price of two, happy mayo, salad, fries and also happy thighs.

137
00:06:46,900 --> 00:06:47,460
Two?

138
00:06:47,460 --> 00:06:48,020
Four.

139
00:06:48,620 --> 00:06:49,180
Four.

140
00:06:49,340 --> 00:06:49,580
Fries?

141
00:06:50,450 --> 00:06:52,820
To drink: Pepsi, light Pepsi, or Happy Juice?

142
00:06:52,820 --> 00:06:53,700
Just water.

143
00:06:54,380 --> 00:06:55,880
Water wouldn't be worth it for you.

144
00:06:56,040 --> 00:06:56,860
So Pepsi?

145
00:06:57,600 --> 00:06:58,580
Runs and a Pepsi!

146
00:06:58,900 --> 00:06:59,980
Runs, Pepsi, got it!

147
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:00,900
Runs, got it!

148
00:07:02,150 --> 00:07:04,950
And that's 420 crowns, please.

149
00:07:08,850 --> 00:07:10,250
Runs, Pepsi, please.

150
00:07:10,760 --> 00:07:11,320
Got it.

151
00:07:11,460 --> 00:07:12,020
Coming up.

152
00:07:14,050 --> 00:07:15,150
Team huddle!

153
00:07:17,950 --> 00:07:19,910
So, for whom do the fries toll?

154
00:07:19,910 --> 00:07:28,140
Well, I'm going to Marik's.

155
00:07:28,200 --> 00:07:28,580
Nowhere.

156
00:07:29,310 --> 00:07:30,990
Ivushka, the beer relay starts soon.

157
00:07:31,070 --> 00:07:32,470
They put me up against the Nusle guys.

158
00:07:32,550 --> 00:07:34,110
Someone from the team can fill in for him.

159
00:07:34,550 --> 00:07:35,350
What team?

160
00:07:35,510 --> 00:07:36,650
You said relay, right?

161
00:07:36,650 --> 00:07:38,750
For the Nusle guys I'm enough on my own.

162
00:07:39,100 --> 00:07:40,740
I need to quiz you on the way home.

163
00:07:40,920 --> 00:07:41,380
Ivushka.

164
00:07:41,660 --> 00:07:43,680
Dad said I should check if you can find your way.

165
00:07:43,780 --> 00:07:44,600
I found it on Sunday.

166
00:07:45,040 --> 00:07:46,820
Yeah, but you left on Thursday.

167
00:07:46,820 --> 00:07:50,450
And yesterday we picked you up at the train depot in Prague South.

168
00:07:50,850 --> 00:07:53,550
Trams and handcars should be more clearly differentiated.

169
00:07:53,660 --> 00:07:54,120
Sit down.

170
00:07:59,360 --> 00:07:59,820
Marik's.

171
00:08:02,050 --> 00:08:03,870
Ivushka, maps only confuse people.

172
00:08:04,150 --> 00:08:05,990
Yeah, a real man doesn't need a map.

173
00:08:05,990 --> 00:08:06,770
Right, Mr. Ozzak?

174
00:08:07,150 --> 00:08:12,550
Like that time you said the same at the orienteering event, and we ended up fishing you out of Macocha.

175
00:08:12,950 --> 00:08:14,150
Which way will you go from Marik's?

176
00:08:14,410 --> 00:08:14,850
Right.

177
00:08:15,250 --> 00:08:16,150
Wrong, straight.

178
00:08:16,190 --> 00:08:17,010
You can't go straight.

179
00:08:17,170 --> 00:08:17,510
Why?

180
00:08:18,150 --> 00:08:19,750
Because right in front of the door there's a trench.

181
00:08:21,050 --> 00:08:22,050
Can't you cross it?

182
00:08:22,220 --> 00:08:23,960
With a footbridge, Libal apparently botched the roof on the outhouse.

183
00:08:24,100 --> 00:08:24,860
Everyone goes right.

184
00:08:24,960 --> 00:08:26,120
But there's nothing to the right.

185
00:08:26,280 --> 00:08:26,960
There's a sewer.

186
00:08:27,850 --> 00:08:29,140
You go through the sewer?

187
00:08:29,150 --> 00:08:30,150
It's a shortcut.

188
00:08:30,250 --> 00:08:32,350
And it always spits us out...

189
00:08:32,450 --> 00:08:34,750
Right in this bakery at Pece.

190
00:08:35,150 --> 00:08:36,590
You go through a bakery?

191
00:08:36,750 --> 00:08:38,070
Nobody minds.

192
00:08:38,350 --> 00:08:39,830
Everyone at Pece is snoring anyway.

193
00:08:40,250 --> 00:08:43,350
But Mr. Ozzak, you're pointing at the Strasnice crematorium.

194
00:08:43,650 --> 00:08:46,210
Those are the Furnaces, Ivushka.

195
00:08:46,650 --> 00:08:47,550
That's what I'm saying.

196
00:08:48,150 --> 00:08:49,320
Maps only confuse people.

197
00:08:49,320 --> 00:08:51,360
It is true that it's much shorter.

198
00:08:51,680 --> 00:08:52,920
And without a map.

199
00:08:53,820 --> 00:08:57,900
If he's so good, then why does he always end up lost in Barikadniku park, two streets from here?

200
00:08:58,060 --> 00:08:59,460
That park is cursed.

201
00:08:59,950 --> 00:09:02,550
And the guard there is a real swine, he always points me the wrong way on purpose.

202
00:09:02,750 --> 00:09:03,260
A guard.

203
00:09:03,750 --> 00:09:04,160
In a park.

204
00:09:04,160 --> 00:09:04,680
Sure.

205
00:09:05,150 --> 00:09:06,620
Does he have a flat cap and a broom?

206
00:09:07,150 --> 00:09:08,540
There's no guard in the park.

207
00:09:08,540 --> 00:09:11,300
But there is a statue of Marshal Konev, hidden in the lilacs.

208
00:09:12,100 --> 00:09:14,400
Alright, why would a statue show Ozzak the way?

209
00:09:14,660 --> 00:09:16,700
His right hand is pointing toward the exit.

210
00:09:16,840 --> 00:09:17,820
Not toward the exit!

211
00:09:17,820 --> 00:09:18,500
Toward the hole in the fence!

212
00:09:19,050 --> 00:09:23,550
So now that I know I'm not gonna talk to that crook anymore, can I go?

213
00:09:23,610 --> 00:09:24,610
Fine, go.

214
00:09:25,850 --> 00:09:37,580
Hello, Tomas.

215
00:09:37,580 --> 00:09:38,100
Hey.

216
00:09:38,320 --> 00:09:40,350
What happened?

217
00:09:41,050 --> 00:09:43,150
The cops woke me up at five in the morning.

218
00:09:43,550 --> 00:09:44,250
Ozzak?

219
00:09:45,550 --> 00:09:47,290
They found him sleeping in the metro at Flora.

220
00:09:47,350 --> 00:09:48,850
Line A didn't run for an hour because of him.

221
00:09:49,650 --> 00:09:51,050
This is going to be embarrassing today.

222
00:09:51,450 --> 00:09:53,050
Too bad it wasn't you.

223
00:09:53,450 --> 00:09:54,050
Excuse me?

224
00:09:55,750 --> 00:09:56,450
See?

225
00:09:56,950 --> 00:09:57,950
Leos again.

226
00:09:59,380 --> 00:10:01,160
He rode a motorcycle across the Charles Bridge?

227
00:10:01,380 --> 00:10:02,520
And naked, Tomas, naked.

228
00:10:02,950 --> 00:10:04,050
Stefan's work.

229
00:10:04,250 --> 00:10:05,950
That can't possibly work.

230
00:10:06,250 --> 00:10:06,820
Can't?

231
00:10:07,150 --> 00:10:09,250
Today they offered him to host the Prague Spring festival.

232
00:10:10,850 --> 00:10:12,550
Have you figured out what you're going to do?

233
00:10:14,350 --> 00:10:16,270
Well, I could trample tulips in the park.

234
00:10:16,270 --> 00:10:16,890
Like Volka.

235
00:10:17,250 --> 00:10:19,550
Attacks on public greenery are passe.

236
00:10:20,250 --> 00:10:22,650
What's the most daring thing you can think of?

237
00:10:24,450 --> 00:10:25,550
I won't pay my rent.

238
00:10:26,560 --> 00:10:28,020
What's daring about that?

239
00:10:28,180 --> 00:10:29,380
You don't know our building manager.

240
00:10:29,650 --> 00:10:31,020
Brave move, Tomas.

241
00:10:31,350 --> 00:10:34,450
Have you ever read in the tabloids about someone beaten with a rag?

242
00:10:34,950 --> 00:10:36,190
So what should I do?

243
00:10:36,250 --> 00:10:37,170
I'm no tiger.

244
00:10:40,150 --> 00:10:41,190
I've got an idea.

245
00:10:41,190 --> 00:10:41,710
What?

246
00:10:42,550 --> 00:10:44,010
You'll go to Cafe Slavia for coffee.

247
00:10:44,450 --> 00:10:46,010
And I'll come up to you for an autograph.

248
00:10:46,450 --> 00:10:47,750
What's daring about that?

249
00:10:48,050 --> 00:10:49,450
I'll be wearing only a bra.

250
00:10:50,550 --> 00:10:51,810
Only a bra?

251
00:10:51,810 --> 00:10:53,490
I'll obviously be dressed from the waist down.

252
00:10:53,700 --> 00:10:54,940
That's a relief.

253
00:10:57,150 --> 00:11:01,050
I mean, not that I think you've got something horrible down there, no.

254
00:11:03,850 --> 00:11:06,550
On the contrary, I think you've got it quite nice down there.

255
00:11:10,050 --> 00:11:13,250
Which of course doesn't mean I'm in any way interested.

256
00:11:13,350 --> 00:11:16,450
Then at least try to steal something.

257
00:11:21,250 --> 00:11:29,050
Lineup for today's winning match is Jira on sanitation, Zdenda on kitchen, Jura on display, Simca on fries.

258
00:11:29,850 --> 00:11:31,450
That's the same as yesterday.

259
00:11:31,660 --> 00:11:32,220
Yep.

260
00:11:34,150 --> 00:11:36,650
But in volleyball you rotate positions.

261
00:11:36,750 --> 00:11:38,250
I'd like to try the register.

262
00:11:38,450 --> 00:11:40,750
Zdenda, the customer is the ball, got it?

263
00:11:42,450 --> 00:11:45,410
The register needs someone with experience, who can dribble.

264
00:11:45,410 --> 00:11:46,630
Like in volleyball.

265
00:11:46,750 --> 00:11:47,810
But come on, shh!

266
00:11:49,750 --> 00:11:51,450
I have experience with a register.

267
00:11:51,450 --> 00:11:51,890
Oh.

268
00:11:53,350 --> 00:11:59,150
Well, you may not know this, but just a few weeks ago there was a pub here and our Simca was the one serving.

269
00:11:59,550 --> 00:12:03,550
But Happy Chick and a tap room...

270
00:12:04,750 --> 00:12:08,550
It's like if she played volleyball her whole life and then switched to volleyball.

271
00:12:26,950 --> 00:12:29,750
I ran into Lexa at Stefan's doorstep.

272
00:12:34,650 --> 00:12:37,650
Sorry, I had to straighten my back from the railroad ties.

273
00:12:37,810 --> 00:12:39,090
Look, this can't go on.

274
00:12:39,250 --> 00:12:40,610
Someone has to walk you home.

275
00:12:40,950 --> 00:12:42,310
And who, Piskot?

276
00:12:42,650 --> 00:12:44,150
Who's Piskot again?

277
00:12:44,350 --> 00:12:45,250
Libal's son.

278
00:12:45,330 --> 00:12:48,050
Libal was worried I'd get lost again, so he sent him with me.

279
00:12:48,310 --> 00:12:49,110
Great idea.

280
00:12:49,290 --> 00:12:51,010
One drunk walking another drunk home.

281
00:12:51,530 --> 00:12:53,730
Piskot doesn't drink, he's doing a courage challenge.

282
00:12:53,850 --> 00:12:54,870
A courage challenge?

283
00:12:54,930 --> 00:12:55,690
He's a boy scout.

284
00:12:55,830 --> 00:12:57,230
What's courageous about not drinking?

285
00:12:58,430 --> 00:13:00,710
Going to a pub and leaving his drink untouched takes guts.

286
00:13:00,850 --> 00:13:02,990
You should stick with a friend like that.

287
00:13:03,090 --> 00:13:03,870
I was holding onto him.

288
00:13:04,150 --> 00:13:06,150
Not well enough, since you ended up on the tracks.

289
00:13:06,550 --> 00:13:07,950
He's the one who dragged me there.

290
00:13:08,150 --> 00:13:16,650
We got lost in the park again, so first he spent an hour looking for an anthill to find north, then we looked at stars for two hours, and when it started raining, he said, there's a cave in that hill, we'll wait till dawn.

291
00:13:16,650 --> 00:13:19,550
Jesus, alright, I'll wait for you tonight.

292
00:13:19,650 --> 00:13:22,650
Tomas, tonight you have other plans.

293
00:13:28,250 --> 00:13:29,250
Work it out with Iva.

294
00:13:38,700 --> 00:13:40,040
I don't understand how you can eat that.

295
00:13:40,120 --> 00:13:41,060
It makes me want to puke.

296
00:13:41,850 --> 00:13:42,950
That's just the first impression.

297
00:13:43,620 --> 00:13:45,500
Once you take a bite, you can't stop.

298
00:13:46,000 --> 00:13:47,640
Can't you eat that at home?

299
00:13:48,450 --> 00:13:52,180
Mom says she smells that stink all day at work, so we should eat it outside.

300
00:13:52,180 --> 00:13:52,660
Want some?

301
00:13:53,250 --> 00:13:53,700
No thanks.

302
00:13:53,950 --> 00:13:54,660
I have risotto.

303
00:13:55,050 --> 00:13:56,380
At least I know what's in it.

304
00:13:56,750 --> 00:13:57,550
Come on.

305
00:13:57,720 --> 00:13:59,300
Everything is made from first-class ingredients.

306
00:13:59,300 --> 00:14:05,450
Perfect quality and natural origin of all materials used is guaranteed by the Melovosice Company.

307
00:14:06,550 --> 00:14:09,820
Sasha, could you go with me to the park tonight to pick up Ozzak?

308
00:14:09,820 --> 00:14:11,340
Dad can't, and I'm scared to go alone.

309
00:14:11,750 --> 00:14:12,450
I'll go.

310
00:14:12,500 --> 00:14:13,280
Thanks, Lexa.

311
00:14:13,360 --> 00:14:14,660
I'd rather be scared than grossed out.

312
00:14:16,150 --> 00:14:18,050
What if a mean dog comes at us?

313
00:14:19,150 --> 00:14:20,550
Then we'll take Lexa too.

314
00:14:21,850 --> 00:14:23,250
But Lexa is scared of dogs.

315
00:14:24,010 --> 00:14:24,970
That's fine.

316
00:14:24,970 --> 00:14:27,710
We'll trip him, the dog goes after him, and we run.

317
00:14:31,550 --> 00:14:33,020
What if a pervert comes at us?

318
00:14:33,020 --> 00:14:33,800
Same thing.

319
00:14:42,250 --> 00:14:43,850
Homemade cherry liqueur, want some?

320
00:14:45,180 --> 00:14:45,660
Pour me one.

321
00:14:46,550 --> 00:14:48,350
Since we're the team...

322
00:14:48,750 --> 00:14:51,550
Pour me some too, I'm all dried out from that eternal juicing.

323
00:14:53,450 --> 00:14:57,080
In the other Happy Chicks they rotate normally, I asked my brother.

324
00:14:57,250 --> 00:14:58,650
He plays volleyball there too.

325
00:14:59,550 --> 00:15:04,650
I don't care about the fries or the runs, but his constant yapping...

326
00:15:04,950 --> 00:15:08,250
That moron knows nothing about volleyball.

327
00:15:08,650 --> 00:15:10,250
I've been playing it for 20 years.

328
00:15:10,450 --> 00:15:12,050
It's more the "volley" part that bothers me.

329
00:15:16,950 --> 00:15:18,050
So we don't forget.

330
00:15:20,650 --> 00:15:22,650
Jura, you don't have to be afraid around me.

331
00:15:23,250 --> 00:15:24,450
We're one team.

332
00:15:24,840 --> 00:15:25,960
Clink glasses with us.

333
00:15:25,960 --> 00:15:27,550
There'll be another chance.

334
00:15:28,050 --> 00:15:31,250
Rudi, why won't you let anyone on the register?

335
00:15:31,770 --> 00:15:32,250
What?

336
00:15:32,330 --> 00:15:33,070
What do you mean I won't?

337
00:15:33,070 --> 00:15:37,450
When you went to the bathroom, you tripped the circuit breaker just in case, so you wouldn't have to switch.

338
00:15:39,150 --> 00:15:40,340
That was to save power.

339
00:15:40,340 --> 00:15:40,820
Right.

340
00:15:41,950 --> 00:15:45,150
And when you went to get soap, you accidentally took the cash registers with you?

341
00:15:47,140 --> 00:15:48,260
Look, don't bullshit us.

342
00:15:48,260 --> 00:15:49,100
We're your team, aren't we?

343
00:15:53,750 --> 00:15:54,230
Fine.

344
00:15:56,050 --> 00:15:58,370
I got a tip that Mishon is coming for us.

345
00:15:58,750 --> 00:15:59,650
And who's that?

346
00:16:00,450 --> 00:16:03,050
An inspector from the customer care department.

347
00:16:03,540 --> 00:16:06,160
Jesus, so when you spot him, you jump behind the register?

348
00:16:06,640 --> 00:16:08,460
Simca, Mishon is a master of disguise.

349
00:16:09,250 --> 00:16:10,850
And extremely cunning.

350
00:16:10,880 --> 00:16:13,980
He always disguises himself as a difficult customer.

351
00:16:14,200 --> 00:16:18,640
For example, he infiltrated the Bratislava Castle branch disguised as a Hungarian.

352
00:16:19,160 --> 00:16:19,860
That pig!

353
00:16:20,350 --> 00:16:28,120
The poor guys refused to serve him, Mishon wrote a report, and headquarters transferred the whole team to Dyjer for two years.

354
00:16:28,120 --> 00:16:29,340
Jesus, Mary!

355
00:16:29,900 --> 00:16:31,720
You're not ready for the register yet.

356
00:16:33,450 --> 00:16:34,950
One little mistake is all it takes.

357
00:16:35,450 --> 00:16:37,390
One badly served customer.

358
00:16:37,390 --> 00:16:37,570
Oops!

359
00:16:38,450 --> 00:16:39,550
Probably dead battery.

360
00:16:39,950 --> 00:16:41,050
Just like in volleyball.

361
00:16:50,250 --> 00:16:51,450
How long before we go?

362
00:16:51,850 --> 00:16:53,150
About two hours.

363
00:17:00,150 --> 00:17:01,650
Lexa, I said flashlight.

364
00:17:02,850 --> 00:17:03,450
Go away.

365
00:17:08,060 --> 00:17:08,660
Uncle.

366
00:17:09,550 --> 00:17:10,350
Leave me alone.

367
00:17:15,050 --> 00:17:16,730
At least we don't have to go to the park.

368
00:17:16,950 --> 00:17:18,050
And be afraid of the pervert.

369
00:17:31,650 --> 00:17:33,650
Tell me what happened.

370
00:17:33,710 --> 00:17:34,490
Leave him alone.

371
00:17:34,990 --> 00:17:37,170
The last time he got home from the pub before midnight was during the floods.

372
00:17:37,190 --> 00:17:38,690
And they had to bring him on a raft.

373
00:17:39,670 --> 00:17:40,990
Something weird happened.

374
00:17:41,510 --> 00:17:42,150
Yeah, it did.

375
00:17:42,150 --> 00:17:44,150
You came home dressed like a pervert.

376
00:17:44,350 --> 00:17:46,450
That's not relevant.

377
00:17:47,450 --> 00:17:51,150
I'll just call Marik's and ask Libal what you were up to there.

378
00:17:52,150 --> 00:17:52,860
He got kicked out.

379
00:17:53,050 --> 00:17:53,900
Libal isn't there anymore.

380
00:17:53,900 --> 00:17:54,240
How come?

381
00:17:54,850 --> 00:17:57,400
Yesterday when he was closing up, he fell into the trench in front of the pub.

382
00:17:57,550 --> 00:17:58,820
Broke both arms.

383
00:17:59,050 --> 00:18:00,240
Oh, that's lovely.

384
00:18:00,350 --> 00:18:03,950
The doctors even say they don't know if he'll ever pour beer again.

385
00:18:04,750 --> 00:18:05,890
Piskot took over for him.

386
00:18:06,150 --> 00:18:06,950
Well, there you go.

387
00:18:07,250 --> 00:18:08,250
What do I see?

388
00:18:08,650 --> 00:18:14,250
He brought his scout buddies, pours beer into mess kits and won't give any to anyone who doesn't sing something by the Bears.

389
00:18:14,750 --> 00:18:16,250
Even just a little waltz.

390
00:18:16,550 --> 00:18:16,950
Dad.

391
00:18:17,550 --> 00:18:20,110
So I told them what I think of their music.

392
00:18:20,250 --> 00:18:21,150
Oh boy.

393
00:18:21,350 --> 00:18:26,150
And they told me that if I ever show up there again, I'll find out what it's like when your tongue hits a broken tooth.

394
00:18:37,440 --> 00:18:39,200
Sorry, I'm a bit late.

395
00:18:39,300 --> 00:18:40,820
There's a terrible mess on the street.

396
00:18:40,820 --> 00:18:42,660
A child on a tricycle supposedly fell into a sewer.

397
00:18:43,650 --> 00:18:44,310
Oh God.

398
00:18:45,750 --> 00:18:51,170
I'll return it right away, I...

399
00:18:51,170 --> 00:18:51,710
Are you insane?!

400
00:18:52,350 --> 00:18:56,150
Do you want to be forever known as the guy who throws kids into sewers?

401
00:18:57,870 --> 00:18:58,390
Howdy.

402
00:18:59,480 --> 00:19:00,160
Hello.

403
00:19:00,850 --> 00:19:01,550
Well, thanks.

404
00:19:02,050 --> 00:19:03,150
I've made my money today.

405
00:19:03,150 --> 00:19:06,250
A child in a sewer is better than Brozova in bath.

406
00:19:06,660 --> 00:19:07,680
You two know each other?

407
00:19:07,880 --> 00:19:09,840
That's Mr. Pastyrik from Blesk tabloid.

408
00:19:09,900 --> 00:19:11,540
Stefan works with him often.

409
00:19:11,720 --> 00:19:12,240
Pastyrik?

410
00:19:12,580 --> 00:19:13,100
Pacovsky.

411
00:19:13,160 --> 00:19:14,320
Is the child okay?

412
00:19:15,350 --> 00:19:17,850
Don't even mention that little brat.

413
00:19:18,150 --> 00:19:22,260
I had to cough up five grand to get him to be thrown in again.

414
00:19:22,750 --> 00:19:23,950
Thrown in again?

415
00:19:24,850 --> 00:19:28,390
By the time I got there, the little rascal had climbed out on his own.

416
00:19:28,390 --> 00:19:29,350
But then what?

417
00:19:30,150 --> 00:19:33,450
Newspapers don't write themselves, do they?

418
00:19:33,950 --> 00:19:36,050
So what scandal shall we commit?

419
00:19:36,060 --> 00:19:37,500
I've got it figured out.

420
00:19:37,500 --> 00:19:40,250
Impoverished singer caught stealing in a supermarket.

421
00:19:40,680 --> 00:19:41,280
Good.

422
00:19:41,540 --> 00:19:43,040
Stefan said you're talented.

423
00:19:43,040 --> 00:19:46,250
I am not going to steal anywhere.

424
00:19:46,260 --> 00:19:47,140
What if I got caught?

425
00:19:47,300 --> 00:19:47,980
That's the whole point.

426
00:19:48,550 --> 00:19:51,040
I'd do it around four, when Harold's is packed.

427
00:19:51,250 --> 00:19:53,700
At five you're at the police station, at six home, and tomorrow in the papers.

428
00:19:53,700 --> 00:19:54,620
That won't work.

429
00:19:55,650 --> 00:19:58,480
At four there's a neo-Nazi rally at Palacky Square, so...

430
00:19:58,480 --> 00:19:59,280
Neo-Nazis?

431
00:19:59,280 --> 00:20:00,650
Why didn't you tell me?

432
00:20:00,950 --> 00:20:02,450
We only talked them into it today.

433
00:20:02,750 --> 00:20:03,950
Beautiful, isn't it?

434
00:20:04,150 --> 00:20:05,450
You'll stand up to fascism.

435
00:20:07,220 --> 00:20:08,220
Have you lost your mind?

436
00:20:08,220 --> 00:20:12,420
According to Stefan, resistance to violence is the second-best way of self-promotion.

437
00:20:12,420 --> 00:20:13,600
And what's the first?

438
00:20:13,760 --> 00:20:14,180
Violence.

439
00:20:15,090 --> 00:20:16,550
Yeah, blood sells.

440
00:20:17,150 --> 00:20:18,350
I'll photograph that with pleasure.

441
00:20:20,550 --> 00:20:24,250
I'll photograph you and Mr. Pacovsky on Palacky Square.

442
00:20:24,780 --> 00:20:26,020
With pleasure.

443
00:20:35,350 --> 00:20:36,250
Oh God, are you alright?

444
00:20:36,960 --> 00:20:38,880
I couldn't do nothing, I snuck in there in disguise.

445
00:20:39,700 --> 00:20:41,380
And if they'd found me out, I loved you.

446
00:20:42,750 --> 00:20:43,650
Where's bro?

447
00:20:43,730 --> 00:20:46,550
No idea, he was hugging me too and asking what my blood type is.

448
00:20:46,770 --> 00:20:48,250
Tell him I loved him too.

449
00:20:48,390 --> 00:20:49,690
Yeah, he's sending you the same message.

450
00:20:49,850 --> 00:20:50,210
Great.

451
00:21:46,750 --> 00:21:47,650
One Pepsi, will that be all?

452
00:21:48,400 --> 00:21:48,660
Yes.

453
00:21:52,550 --> 00:21:53,750
Oh, sorry, some extra fries fell in there by mistake.

454
00:21:55,680 --> 00:21:57,260
Should I call the manager to cancel it?

455
00:21:57,740 --> 00:21:58,680
Oh, leave them.

456
00:21:58,960 --> 00:22:00,060
That's very kind.

457
00:22:00,220 --> 00:22:00,840
One fries.

458
00:22:01,120 --> 00:22:01,900
Fries are up.

459
00:22:02,040 --> 00:22:02,520
Fries, got it.

460
00:22:03,220 --> 00:22:03,780
199.

461
00:22:05,250 --> 00:22:06,750
Oh, thanks.

462
00:22:06,810 --> 00:22:07,610
Enjoy your meal.

463
00:22:07,710 --> 00:22:07,990
Thanks.

464
00:22:08,230 --> 00:22:08,750
Goodbye.

465
00:22:08,830 --> 00:22:09,350
Goodbye.

466
00:22:10,550 --> 00:22:15,050
And they said the Badger tricks wouldn't work here.

467
00:22:19,420 --> 00:22:19,980
I don't know.

468
00:22:21,650 --> 00:22:23,050
Want something?

469
00:22:24,050 --> 00:22:24,950
I want the Badger.

470
00:22:25,350 --> 00:22:26,450
The Badger is gone.

471
00:22:26,650 --> 00:22:30,280
The Badger may be gone, but you can get excellent chicken at a great price.

472
00:22:30,280 --> 00:22:30,760
Want chicken?

473
00:22:31,850 --> 00:22:33,970
I want everything to go back to the way it was.

474
00:22:33,970 --> 00:22:35,270
A real man like this.

475
00:22:35,730 --> 00:22:38,590
He'll surely appreciate our 300-gram Happy Slab.

476
00:22:38,850 --> 00:22:39,830
Got any shots?

477
00:22:40,450 --> 00:22:41,850
We unfortunately don't carry alcohol.

478
00:22:41,990 --> 00:22:42,510
Pepsi?

479
00:22:42,710 --> 00:22:43,230
What?

480
00:22:43,510 --> 00:22:44,030
Beer?

481
00:22:45,310 --> 00:22:47,290
I see you're a demanding customer.

482
00:22:47,310 --> 00:22:47,910
I've got it.

483
00:22:48,070 --> 00:22:50,890
Beer is yellow with foam, so a banana shake.

484
00:22:51,670 --> 00:22:52,470
Who is that?

485
00:22:53,550 --> 00:22:54,250
That's the boss.

486
00:22:54,460 --> 00:22:55,740
And can't he give the guy a beer?

487
00:22:55,820 --> 00:22:57,100
A lager, a porter, anything?

488
00:22:57,160 --> 00:22:58,420
No, but I could offer the Lucky Six.

489
00:22:58,710 --> 00:22:58,870
What?

490
00:22:59,170 --> 00:23:02,050
Two wings, two thighs, and two bishops in a delicious chili sauce.

491
00:23:02,290 --> 00:23:02,810
Rudi, leave him.

492
00:23:03,030 --> 00:23:03,790
Are you crazy?

493
00:23:04,130 --> 00:23:05,570
That's obviously Mishon.

494
00:23:05,730 --> 00:23:08,870
And with the Lucky Six you can choose one of our plush toys.

495
00:23:09,770 --> 00:23:10,290
A donkey.

496
00:23:11,550 --> 00:23:13,550
That's not Mishon, that's Ozzak.

497
00:23:13,960 --> 00:23:15,000
How do you know?

498
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:17,750
He's a friend who used to come to my pub.

499
00:23:17,800 --> 00:23:18,320
Seriously?

500
00:23:18,580 --> 00:23:19,100
Yeah.

501
00:23:20,050 --> 00:23:23,600
So I've been playing the fool because of some vagrant, I'm used to going out boozing.

502
00:23:23,600 --> 00:23:25,060
I was only here to have a beer.

503
00:23:25,080 --> 00:23:25,940
You'll get nothing.

504
00:23:26,750 --> 00:23:28,350
Go to some bar, stop wasting our time.

505
00:23:29,610 --> 00:23:30,290
I'm out of here.

506
00:23:31,050 --> 00:23:31,870
I apologize.

507
00:23:32,350 --> 00:23:33,350
You should.

508
00:23:34,010 --> 00:23:34,650
Here you go.

509
00:23:36,650 --> 00:23:39,550
I'm Cyril Mishon from the customer care department.

510
00:23:40,680 --> 00:23:43,200
You refused to serve a customer.

511
00:23:43,340 --> 00:23:44,000
But he...

512
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:46,120
He is a customer like any other.

513
00:23:46,460 --> 00:23:50,580
I'll just go change in the bathroom and then we'll write it up in your office.

514
00:23:55,410 --> 00:23:56,050
See?

515
00:23:56,950 --> 00:23:58,550
Now you could use a shot too.

516
00:24:08,120 --> 00:24:10,000
Finally, Tomas, are you alright?

517
00:24:10,320 --> 00:24:11,340
The neo-Nazis didn't show up.

518
00:24:11,540 --> 00:24:13,260
Then you should have done the Nazi salute yourself.

519
00:24:15,250 --> 00:24:17,140
Woman, you've completely lost it.

520
00:24:17,450 --> 00:24:18,150
Yeah, probably.

521
00:24:18,750 --> 00:24:21,450
Trying to save the career of such a loser.

522
00:24:21,460 --> 00:24:22,080
What?

523
00:24:23,050 --> 00:24:24,060
What do you mean, loser?

524
00:24:24,060 --> 00:24:24,520
Loser!

525
00:24:26,150 --> 00:24:27,740
I'm a decent person!

526
00:24:27,740 --> 00:24:28,180
No, you're a coward!

527
00:24:29,250 --> 00:24:30,420
A plain coward!

528
00:24:30,420 --> 00:24:32,020
Me, a coward?!

529
00:24:32,020 --> 00:24:33,320
A total coward!

530
00:24:33,400 --> 00:24:35,200
You couldn't even raise your hand?!

531
00:24:35,200 --> 00:24:36,020
Me, a coward!

532
00:24:36,020 --> 00:24:37,080
Me, a coward!

533
00:24:37,080 --> 00:24:37,300
Coward!

534
00:24:37,400 --> 00:24:38,260
Plain coward!

535
00:24:38,440 --> 00:24:39,060
Coward!

536
00:24:39,260 --> 00:24:39,880
Coward!

537
00:24:42,950 --> 00:24:43,650
And you should see.

538
00:24:50,450 --> 00:24:52,750
That was that...

539
00:24:52,850 --> 00:24:55,950
It was, well no, it wasn't.

540
00:24:56,700 --> 00:24:57,300
Obviously.

541
00:24:58,120 --> 00:24:59,080
You're married.

542
00:24:59,280 --> 00:25:00,520
I know.

543
00:25:01,050 --> 00:25:04,490
And we're coworkers.

544
00:25:04,490 --> 00:25:04,710
Yes.

545
00:25:05,670 --> 00:25:07,290
I'm married.

546
00:25:07,390 --> 00:25:08,230
I know, I know.

547
00:25:12,250 --> 00:25:17,450
Well, I have kissed an older woman a few times before.

548
00:25:19,650 --> 00:25:23,950
I mean, not that you're in any way old.

549
00:25:24,750 --> 00:25:27,250
It's actually the opposite.

550
00:25:27,650 --> 00:25:30,150
On the contrary, I think that for your age you...

551
00:25:30,150 --> 00:25:30,510
Tomas.

552
00:25:30,650 --> 00:25:30,890
Yes?

553
00:25:33,850 --> 00:25:35,450
Next time just do the Nazi salute.

554
00:25:46,650 --> 00:25:49,950
This is culture minister, a welcome address.

555
00:25:49,950 --> 00:25:50,590
Hush.

556
00:25:54,260 --> 00:25:58,320
So how did it go?

557
00:26:03,450 --> 00:26:04,350
I'll miss you.

558
00:26:04,550 --> 00:26:07,150
He didn't fire you over something this stupid, did he?

559
00:26:07,650 --> 00:26:10,350
No, but you guys.

560
00:26:12,150 --> 00:26:13,150
As in, us?

561
00:26:13,650 --> 00:26:19,220
He said that with a team that drinks alcohol at work and constantly questions my authority, I was simply bound to fail.

562
00:26:20,950 --> 00:26:22,950
On Monday they're sending me some students.

563
00:26:23,750 --> 00:26:24,550
Wait.

564
00:26:24,850 --> 00:26:27,450
So you sacrificed us to save your own job?

565
00:26:27,550 --> 00:26:28,710
I had to.

566
00:26:29,150 --> 00:26:30,450
I'm the captain.

567
00:26:32,250 --> 00:26:34,450
A captain leaves the ship last.

568
00:26:37,250 --> 00:26:39,850
You know how we'd settle this with the boys in volleyball?

569
00:26:41,050 --> 00:26:45,750
No, no, in boxing.

570
00:26:57,250 --> 00:26:57,950
Yes, thank you.

571
00:26:59,250 --> 00:26:59,950
Goodbye.

572
00:27:04,650 --> 00:27:06,520
Tomas, they're fighting over you.

573
00:27:06,520 --> 00:27:06,640
What?

574
00:27:08,050 --> 00:27:09,450
The 25th Sluknov, the 27th

575
00:27:10,150 --> 00:27:12,170
Jestrebi and the 4th Kostelec again.

576
00:27:12,210 --> 00:27:14,550
The principal called, the whole school wants you.

577
00:27:14,790 --> 00:27:16,690
I told you it would work without a scandal.

578
00:27:24,550 --> 00:27:25,550
What's this supposed to mean?

579
00:27:26,250 --> 00:27:27,450
Stefan was right.

580
00:27:27,650 --> 00:27:29,150
Nudity works great.

581
00:27:29,350 --> 00:27:32,050
But that's not me.

582
00:27:32,750 --> 00:27:36,250
I mean, the top is me, but the bottom is completely different.

583
00:27:39,550 --> 00:27:41,650
Not smaller, different.

584
00:27:42,850 --> 00:27:44,850
The bottom is of course the Prime Minister.

585
00:27:45,550 --> 00:27:46,550
Pabecky said,

586
00:27:46,750 --> 00:27:49,060
when reality fails, it's time for photomontage.

587
00:27:49,550 --> 00:27:50,600
But that's fraud.

588
00:27:51,050 --> 00:27:52,750
That's show business, Tomas.

589
00:28:02,750 --> 00:28:03,550
Oh, not again.

590
00:28:05,450 --> 00:28:07,350
Goodbye, come again.

591
00:28:10,350 --> 00:28:11,650
For whom do the fries toll?
